{"title_page": "Behind the Planet of the Apes", "text_new": "{{italic title}}\n{{refimprove|date=May 2016}}\n\n'''''Behind the Planet of the Apes''''' is a 1998 American television [[documentary]] directed by Kevin Burns and David Comtois who also co-wrote it with Brian Anthony and produced by [[Foxstar Productions]].\n\n==Premise==\nIt focuses on the five films in the original ''[[Planet of the Apes]]'' series, and is hosted and narrated by [[Roddy McDowall]], who played Cornelius in the 1968 film ''[[Planet of the Apes (film)|Planet of the Apes]]'' and ''[[Escape from the Planet of the Apes]]'' and his son Caesar in ''[[Conquest of the Planet of the Apes]]'' and ''[[Battle for the Planet of the Apes]]''. The documentary premiered on [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]] to commemorate the thirtieth anniversary of the first 1968 film.<ref name=\"Greene1998\">{{cite book|author=Eric Greene|title=*Planet of the Apes* as American Myth: Race, Politics, and Popular Culture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZyIiApfhWngC&pg=PR15|year=1998|publisher=Wesleyan University Press|isbn=978-0-8195-6329-3|chapter=preface}}</ref>\n\nThe documentary discusses the ideas and works that led to the production of the films and franchise, including two television series, one live action and one animated series for children. The documentary begins with the [[Planet of the Apes (novel)|original novel]] written by author [[Pierre Boulle]] and how it caught the interest of producer [[Arthur P. Jacobs]], who brought it to [[20th Century Fox]]. The development and production of each film is discussed, including casting, costume design, filming locations and behind the scenes footage.<ref name=\"Hofstede2001\">{{cite book|author=David Hofstede|title=Planet of the Apes: An Unofficial Companion|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OUZ1T4JwMhQC&pg=PA40|year=2001|publisher=ECW Press|isbn=978-1-55022-446-7|pages=40\u2013}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nAs of the 2005 [[DVD]] release of all five of the classic films, the documentary was also included in the DVD box set.<ref name=\"Pratt2005\">{{cite book|author=Douglas Pratt|title=Doug Pratt's DVD: Movies, Television, Music, Art, Adult, and More!|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vxmg-LuBTWIC&pg=PA934|year=2005|publisher=UNET 2 Corporation|isbn=978-1-932916-01-0|pages=934\u2013}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0207332}}\n\n{{Planet of the Apes}}\n\n[[Category:1998 films]]\n[[Category:1998 television films]]\n[[Category:1990s documentary films]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about films]]\n[[Category:Planet of the Apes]]\n\n{{documentary-tv-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{italic title}}\n{{refimprove|date=May 2016}}\n\n'''''Behind the Planet of the Apes''''' is a 1998 American television [[documentary]] directed by Kevin Burns and David Comtois who also co-wrote it with Brian Anthony and produced by [[Foxstar Productions]].\n\n==Premise==\nIt focuses on the five films in the original ''[[Planet of the Apes]]'' series, and is hosted and narrated by [[Roddy McDowall]], who played Cornelius in the 1968 film ''[[Planet of the Apes (film)|Planet of the Apes]]'' and ''[[Escape from the Planet of the Apes]]'' and his son Caesar in ''[[Conquest of the Planet of the Apes]]'' and ''[[Battle for the Planet of the Apes]]''. The documentary premiered on [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]] to commemorate the thirtieth anniversary of the first 1968 film.<ref name=\"Greene1998\">{{cite book|author=Eric Greene|title=*Planet of the Apes* as American Myth: Race, Politics, and Popular Culture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZyIiApfhWngC&pg=PR15|year=1998|publisher=Wesleyan University Press|isbn=978-0-8195-6329-3|chapter=preface}}</ref>\n\nThe documentary discusses the ideas and works that led to the production of the films and franchise, including two television series, one live action and one animated series for children. The documentary begins with the [[Planet of the Apes (novel)|original novel]] written by author [[Pierre Boulle]] and how it caught the interest of producer [[Arthur P. Jacobs]], who brought it to [[20th Century Fox]]. The development and production of each film is discussed, including casting, costume design, filming locations and behind the scenes footage.<ref name=\"Hofstede2001\">{{cite book|author=David Hofstede|title=Planet of the Apes: An Unofficial Companion|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OUZ1T4JwMhQC&pg=PA40|year=2001|publisher=ECW Press|isbn=978-1-55022-446-7|pages=40\u2013}}</ref>\n\nAs of the 2005 [[DVD]] release of all five of the classic films, the documentary was also included in the DVD box set.<ref name=\"Pratt2005\">{{cite book|author=Douglas Pratt|title=Doug Pratt's DVD: Movies, Television, Music, Art, Adult, and More!|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vxmg-LuBTWIC&pg=PA934|year=2005|publisher=UNET 2 Corporation|isbn=978-1-932916-01-0|pages=934\u2013}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0207332}}\n\n{{Planet of the Apes}}\n\n[[Category:1998 films]]\n[[Category:1998 television films]]\n[[Category:1990s documentary films]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about films]]\n[[Category:Planet of the Apes]]\n\n{{documentary-tv-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "ARZ100", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Behind_the_Planet_of_the_Apes"}
